<section class="article-table-of-contents" data-component="articleToc">
			<ol class="article-table-of-contents__list">
			<ul>
<li><a href="#sec2">The Sustainable HPC Datacenter Approach</a></li>
<li><a href="#sec8">Conclusion</a></li>
<li><a href="#sec9">Acknowledgments</a></li>
<li><a href="#references">References</a></li>
<li><a href="#footnotes">Footnotes</a></li>
</ul>
		</ol>
	</section>
		<div class="article-contents">
			
<div class="article-content entry-content">
		<article><div class="body" lang="en"><section id="sec1" class="sec"><p id="p-1">Advances in the field of computer science, such as very complex simulations, data analysis, or machine learning (ML) in data-driven applications (for example, computational fluid dynamics, large language models) are leading to an increased demand of IT performance and data storage capacity. Therefore, the electricity demands of digital infrastructures in science and industry are increasing. High-performance computing (HPC) has become an enabling technology and a vital tool to greatly reduce the processing and execution time of advanced computing- or data-intensive tasks. An obvious consequence: HPC datacenters (DCs) require an enormous amount of electricity, have volatile demands, and produce notable amounts of waste heat. If not well located, built, and operated, such infrastructures generate a significant <span class="inline-formula"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><msub><mtext>CO</mtext><mn>2</mn></msub></math></span> backpack, and the applications and products that use them inherit the backpack from the computing platform.</p><figure id="F1" class="fig" data-jats-position="float"><div class="image-container"><figure id="attachment_769151" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-769151" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a data-fslightbox="https://cacm.acm.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/cacm-25-01-5113-File005.png" data-type="image" data-caption="" href="https://cacm.acm.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/cacm-25-01-5113-File005.png">
				<img decoding="async" class=" wp-image-769151" src="https://cacm.acm.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/cacm-25-01-5113-File005.png?w=1024" alt="asic system architecture of HPC datacenters " width="814" height="391" srcset="https://cacm.acm.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/cacm-25-01-5113-File005.png 15722w, https://cacm.acm.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/cacm-25-01-5113-File005.png?resize=300,144 300w, https://cacm.acm.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/cacm-25-01-5113-File005.png?resize=768,369 768w, https://cacm.acm.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/cacm-25-01-5113-File005.png?resize=1024,492 1024w, https://cacm.acm.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/cacm-25-01-5113-File005.png?resize=1536,739 1536w, https://cacm.acm.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/cacm-25-01-5113-File005.png?resize=2048,985 2048w" sizes="(max-width: 814px) 100vw, 814px" />
			</a><figcaption id="caption-attachment-769151" class="wp-caption-text"><strong>Figure 1.  Basic system architecture of HPC datacenters located in and distributed among wind turbines.</strong></figcaption></figure></div></figure><p id="p-3">At the same time, society has developed a strong awareness toward sustainability. As a result, energy-intensive infrastructures that try to maximize the use of renewable energy sources (RES), such as photovoltaic and wind energy, are gradually being expanded. Development and operation of such infrastructures with the same reliability of service is quite challenging for a number of reasons. The transformation from centralized power supply, primarily using conventional power plants and generators, to a decentralized infrastructure requires a continuous grid expansion and more sophisticated information and communication technology. Furthermore, methods have to be developed and improved to compensate for the gradually decreasing inertia to ensure grid stability: The inertia of heavy generators resists changes in rotational speed—induced by changes of the electric load in the power system—and thus changes in the produced AC frequency. Hence, the increased deployment of RES decreases the resilience of the power grid to frequency variations.</p><p id="p-4">A functional requirement and constraint is the imperative that the power supply must match the power demand at all times. Achieving this is challenging due to the volatile nature of RES. An approach to ensure this power balance is the successive deployment of energy storage devices and the development of (local) energy management systems. Both support the environmental and economical sustainability of the energy transition. However, in times of oversupply, huge amounts of electricity are still capped on account of grid stability considerations.</p><p id="p-5">Trying to find a practical solution to the main concerns—<i>high power demand</i>, <i><span class="inline-formula"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><msub><mtext>CO</mtext><mn>2</mn></msub></math></span> emission reduction</i>, and <i>volatile power generation</i>—led to the idea of wind turbines (WTs) that house DCs (Figure <a class="xref xref-fig" href="#F1" data-jats-rid="F1" data-jats-ref-type="fig">1</a>). It increases the region&#8217;s own demand for electrical energy and fundamentally improves the sustainable supply of DCs. The adaption to HPC exploits the fact that it is feasible to manage the power profile of specialized DCs. In this way, HPC-DCs can be considered flexible energy consumers in an RES-based energy system. During periods of oversupply, the power demand of the HPC-DC is increased, so the load is served with the power generated onsite. During periods of undersupply, the power profile is properly decreased. In both cases, coordinated management of the IT resources and infrastructures involved is an indispensable prerequisite.</p><p id="p-6">The Germany-wide project “Energy-Optimized Supercomputer Networks Using Wind Energy” (ESN4NW) is devoted to the research and demonstration of the potential of WTs that house HPC-DCs in their towers and supply them with the power generated on site. WTs that house conventional DCs, called <i>windCORES</i><a class="footnote-link xref xref-fn" href="#FNa" data-jats-rid="FNa" data-jats-ref-type="fn"><sup>a</sup></a>, already exist. The main objective of the project is to develop the windCORES infrastructure for the energy-related and thermal management of an HPC cluster located and operated in several WTs. There are various considerations and tasks associated with the development of such an infrastructure. For instance, models for a failure-resistant and energy-efficient operation have to be defined. Furthermore, a dedicated DC infrastructure management platform for distributed HPC clusters deployed in wind farms has to be developed. In addition, to be able to assess and compare the sustainability of the novel DC approach with conventional approaches, a life-cycle assessment model, as well as key performance indicators (KPIs) and metrics for the operation and cooling of the HPC cluster are required.</p><p id="p-7">In the following, the benefits, some challenges, and potential modeling approaches for establishing this sustainable infrastructure are discussed in more detail. This article is divided into three parts. The overview discusses the main objectives and the benefits to be expected from establishing an infrastructure of WT-housed HPC-DCs, while the following section offers some insight into the modeling approaches and control-related concerns to achieve efficient operation and HPC-related goals simultaneously. The final section, before concluding, covers potential methods for assessing and improving the sustainability of this novel DC architecture.</p></section><section id="sec2" class="sec"><h2 class="heading">The Sustainable HPC Datacenter Approach</h2><p id="p-8">In this section, the concept of windCORES housing HPC-DCs, in the following called <i>green (HPC-)DC</i>, is elaborated. Note that despite its name, not only HPC workloads, but various types of workloads with volatile and/or high-energy demand are within the scope of the proposed infrastructure.</p><section id="sec3" class="inline-headings-section"><p data-jats-content-type="inline-heading"><strong>Overview.</strong>  The potential benefits of such a sustainable DC architecture are apparent. First, the technical infrastructure is embedded in an existing facility that shares many needed features. In particular, this considerably improves the carbon footprint of construction. Furthermore, it provides electric connectivity that is higher than that of required embedded HPC systems by a huge margin. Onsite generation allows for a direct and low-loss electric energy supply of HPC servers.</p><p id="p-10">The most striking argument is the reduction or even prevention of power curtailment of RES: The responsible grid operator can influence the power output of the respective wind farm at the substation by adjusting it in accordance with a predetermined setpoint. As the reason for power curtailment is usually due to grid stability considerations (that is, a temporary surplus of power supply), the control mechanism cannot be influenced by the wind farm operator. Such interventions are known as congestion management measures. A strategy for adapting the power profile of an electrical consumer, for example, that of an embedded HPC-DC, resolves this potential energy waste. The correlation of compute power and energy demand is predictable. So, its planned increase during periods of excess wind power or low-power needs in the grid can counteract the waste of (theoretically) available energy. The deployment of multiple HPC nodes among wind power plants can help to unfold their full potential by minimizing power curtailment and, with that, both increase the efficiency of a WT and reduce the operational carbon footprint of the green DC architecture.</p><p id="p-11">Besides energy-related concerns, another feature of WTs becomes usable for high-density IT systems, namely the cooling mechanism. Due to the high power density of HPC-IT, a huge amount of power is dissipated. For a safe operation of the devices, a sophisticated (potentially liquid-based) cooling infrastructure is often used. This will have a negative impact on the so-called power usage efficiency (PUE), a well-known KPI given by the ratio of the total power demand of the DC and the IT power demand. To discharge the resulting waste heat, the physical environment of the IT equipment can be exploited. The tower itself can act as a heat sink. While a large portion of dissipated heat is removed from the servers via the liquid-based cooling system, the heat-sink capacity of the WT tower will be exploited to get rid of the remaining heat, which is still significant, in a free air cooling-fashion. This power can be estimated sufficiently well, provided that the utilization of the IT equipment, their power consumption, the power consumption of the cooling system, and the environmental conditions are known.</p><p id="p-12">Inclusion and adaption of components of the DC infrastructure have the potential to reduce the scale of cooling equipment so that the carbon footprint is further diminished. In addition, using the tower as a heat sink opens up the possibility to have heat flexibility reserves located on site. Thereby, the dissipated heat does not necessarily have to be wasted but can be served to nearby heat customers, further improving the carbon footprint. The infrastructure to be developed must take all these considerations into account. It must continuously adjust the system utilization of the distributed HPC-DC with regard to the volatile, locally available wind power and the thermal limits within the tower of the WT or waste-heat users. The main considerations for this infrastructure are technical and economic feasibility, the use of wind power to its full potential, and the improvement of both the operational carbon footprint and sustainability throughout the life cycle of a real sustainable and green DC.</p></section><section id="sec4" class="inline-headings-section"><p data-jats-content-type="inline-heading"><strong>Modeling and control.</strong>  The control strategy is the energy- and thermal-aware scheduling and activation of HPC-IT resources located in several WTs under various constraints, which can be classified as follows:</p><ol class="list" data-jats-list-type="order"><li class="list-item"><p id="p-14"><b>Computational constraints</b> are concerned with the number and type of available resources (for example, CPU, RAM, and storage) at a certain time instant and the time for servers to be switched on and off.</p></li><li class="list-item"><p id="p-15"><b>Environmental constraints</b> comprise thermal limits due to the heat dissipated in the tower and the weather conditions, available wind power, energy availability of the regional energy grids, local waste heat users, and so on.</p></li><li class="list-item"><p id="p-16"><b>User constraints</b> are mainly concerned with the number and size of compute jobs to be executed and quality of service (QoS) considerations—for example, time-to-solution.</p></li></ol><p id="p-17">Figure <a class="xref xref-fig" href="#F2" data-jats-ref-type="fig" data-jats-rid="F2">2</a> summarizes the principal idea behind the management of this distributed HPC architecture. Unlike conventional DCs, where only <i>available HPC resources</i> were determining the operational management and control of HPC-DCs, there are new directives in the green HPC approach, namely <i>energy availability</i>, <i>waste-heat treatment</i>, and <i>cooling power</i>. That is, regardless of the concrete implementation of the infrastructure, these four aspects are the limiting factors and decisive for job management. Since high availability and fast job execution are essential in the context of HPC, it is important to mention there will be periods where the servers are powered by gray electricity, drawn from the external grid, to execute or finish already-running computations. In particular, the control model does not prohibit grid power consumption for DC operation, implying that power availability itself is not an issue (and constant compute job checkpointing is not a necessity), but seeks a proper trade-off between sustainability and performance.</p><figure id="F2" class="fig" data-jats-position="float"><div class="image-container"><figure id="attachment_769153" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-769153" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a data-fslightbox="https://cacm.acm.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/cacm-25-01-5113-File006.png" data-type="image" data-caption="" href="https://cacm.acm.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/cacm-25-01-5113-File006.png">
				<img decoding="async" class=" wp-image-769153" src="https://cacm.acm.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/cacm-25-01-5113-File006.png?w=1024" alt="Big picture of the green DC job management." width="873" height="392" srcset="https://cacm.acm.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/cacm-25-01-5113-File006.png 13738w, https://cacm.acm.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/cacm-25-01-5113-File006.png?resize=300,135 300w, https://cacm.acm.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/cacm-25-01-5113-File006.png?resize=768,344 768w, https://cacm.acm.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/cacm-25-01-5113-File006.png?resize=1024,459 1024w, https://cacm.acm.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/cacm-25-01-5113-File006.png?resize=1536,689 1536w, https://cacm.acm.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/cacm-25-01-5113-File006.png?resize=2048,919 2048w" sizes="(max-width: 873px) 100vw, 873px" />
			</a><figcaption id="caption-attachment-769153" class="wp-caption-text"><strong>Figure 2.  Big picture of the green DC job management.</strong></figcaption></figure></div></figure><p id="p-19">Due to the high complexity of the green DC architecture, several domains have to be modeled to establish the control model. In the following, a selection of the most important submodels is outlined.</p><section id="sec5" class="inline-headings-section"><p data-jats-content-type="inline-heading"><strong>Datacenter placement strategy.</strong>  For establishing an energy-efficient, distributed HPC infrastructure in a wind farm, it is required to assess the maximum permissible HPC-DC capacity both per wind farm and per WT, and to define easy-to-check decision criteria for optimal DC placement within a wind farm. To this end, an accurate model of the regional energy grid, including thermal and electric flows, and taking spatial and physical constraints into account (for example, power line transmission limits) are necessary. Ideal computing densities in a wind farm are mainly based on historic wind farm operation data and on space limitations of the respective green DCs. It is expected that suitable densities per WT range from 100kW to 1MW, mostly depending on the environmental and climatic conditions of the wind farm&#8217;s location and the space limitations (including heat dissipation capacity) of the individual WTs.</p><p id="p-21">Three main concerns must be taken into account for both the amount of IT resources and the optimal placement of datacenters in a wind farm: <i>wind farm power generation</i>, <i>DC power consumption</i>, and <i>power curtailment</i>. Due to the volatile availability of wind power, an accurate power prediction model of the respective wind farms is indispensable (see Lehneis et al.<a class="reference-link xref xref-bibr" href="#B9" data-jats-ref-type="bibr" data-jats-rid="B9"><sup>9</sup></a>). Moreover, a model needs to map the correlation between IT load and power consumption of HPC-DC resources, which is typically based on regression or artificial neural networks.<a class="reference-link xref xref-bibr" href="#B7" data-jats-ref-type="bibr" data-jats-rid="B7"><sup>7</sup></a><sup>,</sup><a class="reference-link xref xref-bibr" href="#B11" data-jats-ref-type="bibr" data-jats-rid="B11"><sup>11</sup></a><sup>,</sup><a class="reference-link xref xref-bibr" href="#B10" data-jats-ref-type="bibr" data-jats-rid="B10"><sup>10</sup></a> Concerning power curtailment, three main factors can potentially result in a decrease in the total wind power output.</p><ol class="list" data-jats-list-type="order"><li class="list-item"><p id="p-22"><b>Technical limitation</b>. Technical malfunctions or problems (for example, generator overheat, defective converter, and so on).</p></li><li class="list-item"><p id="p-23"><b>Force limitation</b>. Losses or even downtime because of an &#8216;act of nature&#8217; that cannot be influenced by the wind farm operators (for example, overvoltage or storms).</p></li><li class="list-item"><p id="p-24"><b>External limitation</b>. Reduction due to grid-operator-induced power curtailment.</p></li></ol><p id="p-25">Figure <a class="xref xref-fig" href="#F3" data-jats-ref-type="fig" data-jats-rid="F3">3</a> depicts the actual power generation and the proportional contribution of the respective factor to the power reduction of an existing WT, located in North Rhine-Westphalia, Germany, over the course of two years. It shows that 25% of the theoretically available wind power is actually not generated due to the aforementioned restrictions, where the grid-operator-induced power curtailment is the predominant factor in this case. An analysis of wind power data of the corresponding wind farm in which the WT is located—consisting of 16 WTs—shows that, despite the capability and technical feasibility, there was so much (potential) wind energy that was not generated during the considered period due to grid-operator-induced curtailment that, effectively, there is one WT in the wind farm that generates wind power to no avail.</p><figure id="F3" class="fig" data-jats-position="float"><div class="image-container"><figure class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a data-fslightbox="https://cacm.acm.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/3725981_fig03.jpg" data-type="image" data-caption="Figure 3. " href="https://cacm.acm.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/3725981_fig03.jpg">
				<img decoding="async" class="graphic" title="Figure 3. " src="https://cacm.acm.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/3725981_fig03.jpg" alt="A multicolored pie chart shows a breakdown of the actual power generation and power curtailment of a single wind turbine in a wind farm located in North Rhine-Westphalia, Germany, in the period 2021–2022." width="634" height="301" data-image-id="F3" data-image-type="figure" />
			</a><figcaption class="wp-caption-text"><strong>Figure 3.  A breakdown of the actual power generation and power curtailment of a single wind turbine in a wind farm located in North Rhine-Westphalia, Germany, in the period 2021–2022.</strong></figcaption></figure></div></figure><p id="p-27">The objective is to minimize power curtailment by directly using wind power to run the HPC servers in the HPC windCORE. In this way, less power is (supposed to be) injected into the grid, so both the number of grid operator interventions and the amount of power curtailment are reduced substantially. Together with the other power flow models in the local grid, it is possible to specify ideal HPC-DC locations and time intervals where job execution and, with that, high computational power demand, is and is not preferred, respectively.</p></section><section id="sec6" class="inline-headings-section"><p data-jats-content-type="inline-heading"><strong>Control and optimization.</strong>  The control model is the centerpiece of the green HPC operational model. It gathers information from all domains and domain-specific prediction models, takes into account the constraints introduced at the beginning of Modeling and Control section, and schedules HPC-IT resources for job execution in a failure-resistant and energy-efficient manner.</p><p id="p-29">The energy-efficient allocation of (HPC-)DC resources is a topic that is studied extensively.<a class="reference-link xref xref-bibr" href="#B2" data-jats-ref-type="bibr" data-jats-rid="B2"><sup>2</sup></a><sup>,</sup><a class="reference-link xref xref-bibr" href="#B8" data-jats-ref-type="bibr" data-jats-rid="B8"><sup>8</sup></a> It is important to note that conventional solutions to energy-efficient scheduling algorithms are, in general, not applicable to HPC-DCs, as the scheduling principles vastly differ from cloud scheduling paradigms (cf.<a class="reference-link xref xref-bibr" href="#B5" data-jats-ref-type="bibr" data-jats-rid="B5"><sup>5</sup></a>). For example, consolidation is a software solution that seeks to balance the demand for computing resources with the supply of resources (cf.<a class="reference-link xref xref-bibr" href="#B11" data-jats-ref-type="bibr" data-jats-rid="B11"><sup>11</sup></a>). This is often achieved through a runtime migration of virtual machines away from underutilized servers to servers that can execute compute jobs at their maximum capacity. This approach, however, is hard to realize in the context of HPC, as active servers often execute at their maximum capacity already, or there are QoS-induced constraints, such as a time-to-solution threshold, which is why as many servers as possible shall be active at once to guarantee high system utilization and user satisfaction.</p><p id="p-30">Furthermore, as mentioned earlier, the physical environment imposes further constraints on the scheduling algorithm for green DCs compared to conventional HPC-DCs. Having regard to the new directives <i>energy availability</i>, <i>cooling power</i>, and <i>waste heat treatment</i>, alternative and more sophisticated approaches are needed. Two well-known and practically very successful frameworks are candidates worth exploring, namely reinforcement learning (RL)<a class="reference-link xref xref-bibr" href="#B5" data-jats-ref-type="bibr" data-jats-rid="B5"><sup>5</sup></a> and model predictive control (MPC).<a class="reference-link xref xref-bibr" href="#B6" data-jats-ref-type="bibr" data-jats-rid="B6"><sup>6</sup></a> Both approaches can be extended accordingly to fit the context of green HPC-DCs.</p><p id="p-31">In the former, an agent-based scheduling model with an emphasis on performance is proposed. To make use of this innovative model in the context of green DC, it is required to take energy-related and thermal constraints into account, see Figure <a class="xref xref-fig" href="#F2" data-jats-ref-type="fig" data-jats-rid="F2">2</a>. In the latter, the MPC control objective is the thermal-aware server assignment to allocate active servers to areas of high cooling efficiency. Since the green HPC cluster is distributed, it also makes sense to consider distributed MPC approaches, as in Braun et al.<a class="reference-link xref xref-bibr" href="#B3" data-jats-ref-type="bibr" data-jats-rid="B3"><sup>3</sup></a> In principle, a high-level controller generates a global reference signal for the operational state of the total cluster while interacting with local controllers—that is, controllers associated with the respective WT that houses HPC servers. The local controllers, in turn, manage the operational state of the respective local servers and obey the constraints imposed by the global controller.</p><p id="p-32">Obviously, there has to be a trade-off between the mentioned criteria, since sustainability and HPC-related goals cannot be achieved concurrently without making compromises. The main goal is to find an optimal operational strategy for the green HPC-DC, taking both sustainability and performance considerations into account. The operational carbon footprint must be minimized, while simultaneously having regard for the key performance criterion of HPC, namely time-to-solution. Due to these conflicting optimization goals, the natural question arises: What strategy is considered <i>optimal</i> for the green DC? To answer this question, the problem can be modeled as a multicriteria optimization problem.<a class="reference-link xref xref-bibr" href="#B4" data-jats-ref-type="bibr" data-jats-rid="B4"><sup>4</sup></a> It formalizes a number of conflicting objectives and seeks to determine a handful of system configurations that can be considered optimal, as they all minimize the objective function (in a predefined sense). For instance, an emission-low configuration with a poor time-to-solution for compute jobs can be as optimal (with respect to the objective function) as a configuration with better performance but an increased carbon footprint. Clearly, various system configurations imply various operational strategies for the green DC with impact on the control algorithm. To find an optimal control strategy, a multicriteria optimization problem can be defined and included in the control model (see Peitz et al.<a class="reference-link xref xref-bibr" href="#B12" data-jats-ref-type="bibr" data-jats-rid="B12"><sup>12</sup></a> for an MPC-based approach).</p></section></section><section id="sec7" class="inline-headings-section"><p data-jats-content-type="inline-heading"><strong>Sustainability assessment.</strong>  To verify both the ecological and economical sustainability of the novel green HPC-DC architecture, a life-cycle assessment model must be established and the results must be compared with those of conventional HPC-DCs.</p><p id="p-34">The sustainability of the green HPC-DC needs to be evaluated from different points of view. One criterion is the determination of the power demand over the course of a year. Moreover, the carbon footprint has to be estimated with respect to the manufacturing of IT hardware, the system infrastructure, and HPC operation. As wind farms are typically built in more rural areas, it is essential to account for adding high-speed interconnections and proper networking of the distributed HPC-DC infrastructure, for both monetary and carbon footprint reasons.</p><p id="p-35">Note that the life-cycle assessment strongly depends on the control strategy. The choice of system configuration affects the operational life span of IT hardware and the amount of gray electricity consumed by the servers. The reason for the latter is that due to HPC-related concerns (such as QoS obligations toward IT customers), it is not possible to execute (critical) compute jobs exclusively during periods of available wind power. In particular, for a potential analysis of the green HPC infrastructure, a life-cycle assessment is required for different system configurations.</p><p id="p-36">Since DCs are capable of adapting their power profile, and since sustainability is the main concern in the context of green HPC-DCs, it is reasonable for the IT customers and the DC operator to unfold this potential by agreeing on a collaboration. An agreement (including economic incentives) between a DC operator and IT customers that establishes rules for an energy-aware DC operation, while guaranteeing a flexible level of QoS, is a well-known concept called green service-level agreement (greenSLA).<a class="reference-link xref xref-bibr" href="#B1" data-jats-ref-type="bibr" data-jats-rid="B1"><sup>1</sup></a> This type of agreement regulates the decisions regarding energy consumption that can affect the quality of the provided services. Contracts of this kind will have a positive impact on the life-cycle assessment, as it softens the QoS obligations and, with that, offers more opportunities toward a predominantly sustainability-concerned system configuration in the control algorithm.</p></section></section><section id="sec8" class="sec"><h2 class="heading">Conclusion</h2><p id="p-37">This work presents a unique architectural approach to greatly improve the sustainability of energy-intensive computing. A modeling approach for the operational management of a distributed HPC cluster allocated in several towers of WTs, with regard to both sustainability and HPC-related concerns, is proposed. Furthermore, to improve the carbon dioxide balance throughout the life cycle of a green DC, greenSLAs between the DC operator and IT customers are suggested to find an adequate trade-off between energy-aware system operation and user satisfaction for both parties.</p><p id="p-38">In spite of numerous technical and scientific challenges presented in this work, the project has the potential to prove that the digitalization and the steadily increasing power requirement do not attenuate sustainability improvements, and modeling and continuously improving the infrastructure paves the way for a low-emission, or even emission-free, DC operation in the future.</p></section><section id="sec9" class="sec"><h2 class="heading">Acknowledgments</h2><p id="p-39">This work was funded by the German Federal Ministry for Education and Research (BMBF), under grant agreement no. 16ME0619, within the ESN4NW project.</p></section></div><footer class="back"></footer></article>
